00:07:04.750 --> 00:07:10.430
And to work with Andrew, who
is so gifted and so smart,

00:07:10.430 --> 00:07:18.590
and Nate Powell, it's
been a work of love.

00:07:18.590 --> 00:07:23.930
And to see young people
standing in line to get the book,

00:07:23.930 --> 00:07:29.510
to get the book signed, and to take
a seat in the middle of the floor

00:07:29.510 --> 00:07:35.040
at a table, a desk, and read
the book, and as I travel

00:07:35.040 --> 00:07:42.250
around America, different places,
people come up with the book,

00:07:42.250 --> 00:07:46.420
said I'm buying this book for
my son or my brother, my nieces,

00:07:46.420 --> 00:07:50.010
my nephews, so I think
it's a good thing.

00:07:50.010 --> 00:07:51.310
We all should read.

00:07:51.310 --> 00:07:55.660
Books are powerful.

00:07:55.660 --> 00:07:58.860
They can take us places
that we dare to go.

00:07:58.860 --> 00:08:02.450
&gt;&gt; Kojo Nnamdi: I'm glad you
finally got your library card.

00:08:02.450 --> 00:08:03.750
&gt;&gt; Rep. John Lewis: Yes.

00:08:03.750 --> 00:08:06.150
&gt;&gt; Kojo Nnamdi: Before we get
to the third book in the series,

00:08:06.150 --> 00:08:09.090
let's talk a little bit about
why this project took the shape

00:08:09.090 --> 00:08:12.240
that it did as a graphic novel.

00:08:12.240 --> 00:08:17.490
Comics actually have some
ties to civil rights movement.

00:08:17.490 --> 00:08:21.100
When did you first
encounter a comic that spoke

00:08:21.100 --> 00:08:23.470
to the civil rights movement?

00:08:23.470 --> 00:08:27.820
&gt;&gt; In late 1957 or
either early 1958,

00:08:27.820 --> 00:08:31.470
I remember reading a comic book
called Martin Luther King Jr.

00:08:31.470 --> 00:08:34.440
and the Montgomery Story.

00:08:34.440 --> 00:08:39.860 position:56%
It sold for ten cents, and Andrew
would tell you through his research,

00:08:39.860 --> 00:08:44.950
he discovered that Dr.
King helped edit this book.

00:08:44.950 --> 00:08:52.600
This book became like a road map
for those of us that got involved

00:08:52.600 --> 00:08:54.430
in the American civil
rights movement.

00:08:54.430 --> 00:08:58.500
It told the story of Montgomery.

00:08:58.500 --> 00:09:02.650
It spoke about the way of peace,
the way of love, the philosophy

00:09:02.650 --> 00:09:10.330
for nonviolence, how people
organize, how people walked,

00:09:10.330 --> 00:09:16.630
shared rides in cars, church
buses, [inaudible] rides,

00:09:16.630 --> 00:09:19.230
segregated buses in Montgomery.

00:09:19.230 --> 00:09:22.090
In Montgomery during the '50's,

00:09:22.090 --> 00:09:26.950
black and white people couldn't
be seated together on a city bus.

00:09:26.950 --> 00:09:33.450
Even here in Washington, DC, in
1961 during the freedom rise,

00:09:33.450 --> 00:09:36.990
black people and white people
couldn't be seated together leaving

00:09:36.990 --> 00:09:41.130
Washington to travel through
Virginia or North Carolina

00:09:41.130 --> 00:09:44.590
or South Carolina or
Georgia, Alabama, Mississippi.

00:09:44.590 --> 00:09:53.510 position:56%
So public transportation, whether
the train or buses, had been a means

00:09:53.510 --> 00:10:00.970
of carrying the story in the way
of the civil rights movement.

00:10:00.970 --> 00:10:04.790
[Inaudible] those signs that said
white waiting, colored waiting,

00:10:04.790 --> 00:10:08.960
white men, colored men,
white women, colored women.

00:10:08.960 --> 00:10:10.970
And I say to young
people all the time,

00:10:10.970 --> 00:10:17.020
growing up today you won't
see those signs on a bus

00:10:17.020 --> 00:10:19.470
or on a train or a waiting room.

00:10:19.470 --> 00:10:23.920 position:56%
The only place that you'll see
those signs today will be in a book,

00:10:23.920 --> 00:10:27.630
in a museum, or on a video.

00:10:27.630 --> 00:10:30.990
They're gone, and it's my hope
they will never, ever return.

00:10:30.990 --> 00:10:34.340
&gt;&gt; Kojo Nnamdi: Andrew
Aydin, despite the fact

00:10:34.340 --> 00:10:39.010
that the Congressman encountered
that graphic novel of comic

00:10:39.010 --> 00:10:43.380
about Dr. King when he
was just 17 years old,

00:10:43.380 --> 00:10:47.030
you still had a little trouble
convincing your colleagues

00:10:47.030 --> 00:10:51.840
and even the Congressman
himself to write a graphic novel.

00:10:51.840 --> 00:10:59.000
Why did you think this was the
right format for this project?

00:10:59.000 --> 00:11:00.370
&gt;&gt; Andrew Aydin: I
grew up in Atlanta.

00:11:00.370 --> 00:11:02.120
The Congressman has
been my Congressman

00:11:02.120 --> 00:11:03.420
since I was three years old.

00:11:03.420 --> 00:11:07.480
I went to Atlanta Public
Schools, and I heard the story

00:11:07.480 --> 00:11:09.300
of the Civil Rights Movement
over and over and over again.

00:11:09.300 --> 00:11:11.210
I heard it in documentaries.

00:11:11.210 --> 00:11:12.760
I heard it in books.

00:11:12.760 --> 00:11:15.800
I heard people tell the stories.

00:11:15.800 --> 00:11:18.540
But to me, I'd grown
up reading comics.

00:11:18.540 --> 00:11:20.650
It was sort of my salvations,
my refuge, right.

00:11:20.650 --> 00:11:24.260
My father left when I was
four or five years old,

00:11:24.260 --> 00:11:25.560
and it was sort of where I turned.

00:11:25.560 --> 00:11:28.680
I wanted stories of
heroes who wanted justice

00:11:28.680 --> 00:11:31.500
because it was the
right thing to do.

00:11:31.500 --> 00:11:35.920
And that summer [loud tone
noise], should I bebop that?

00:11:35.920 --> 00:11:42.120
[laughter] That summer
of the campaign in 2008,

00:11:42.120 --> 00:11:45.990
Barack Obama was sweeping
through the democratic primaries,

00:11:45.990 --> 00:11:48.590
people in politics were
fundamentally reevaluating the way

00:11:48.590 --> 00:11:52.140
in which they communicate with
young people but with everyone,

00:11:52.140 --> 00:11:55.470
whether it's the internet,
the visual literacy that comes

00:11:55.470 --> 00:11:58.230
with that, or simply just
how you talk to people,

00:11:58.230 --> 00:12:00.770
like what we're willing
to talk about.

00:12:00.770 --> 00:12:04.150
And so as it came down
to the internet campaign

00:12:04.150 --> 00:12:05.690
and the Congressman tells
me about Martin Luther King

00:12:05.690 --> 00:12:08.070
and the Montgomery story, I
mean these were two things

00:12:08.070 --> 00:12:10.060
that were incredibly
important in my life.

00:12:10.060 --> 00:12:12.310
Here I'd spent the whole summer
watching John Lewis tell these

00:12:12.310 --> 00:12:15.610
stories that I had never
heard growing up in Atlanta.

00:12:15.610 --> 00:12:18.830
The story of SNCC, the
story of the young people,

00:12:18.830 --> 00:12:21.500
which was so much different than
the story I had always been told,

00:12:21.500 --> 00:12:24.760
and at the same time the
Congressman was telling me

00:12:24.760 --> 00:12:29.470
that he read a comic book when he
thought about joining the movement.

00:12:29.470 --> 00:12:32.760
I mean, the 24-year-old nerd
just kind of exploded, you know.

00:12:32.760 --> 00:12:39.030
And it felt like it was
okay to be me, right.

00:12:39.030 --> 00:12:43.180
Like oh, maybe it wasn't so weird
for me to like comics after all.

00:12:43.180 --> 00:12:46.070
Maybe it was all the other people
who put them down who were wrong.

00:12:46.070 --> 00:12:51.730
And so when I try to think, you
know, there should be a comic book

00:12:51.730 --> 00:12:55.850
about John Lewis' life,
it was in a sense

00:12:55.850 --> 00:12:59.010
to show everyone what I
had just seen that summer,

00:12:59.010 --> 00:13:01.260
what I had witnessed first-hand.

00:13:01.260 --> 00:13:05.110
And hearing John Lewis tell the
story, seeing him acted out,

00:13:05.110 --> 00:13:10.840
seeing him in front of you, that
was a big part of it for me,

00:13:10.840 --> 00:13:13.280
and so trying to find a way to
capture that experience and put it

00:13:13.280 --> 00:13:17.340
down on paper, words alone
could not do it the justice

00:13:17.340 --> 00:13:20.230
that it needed, so--

00:13:20.230 --> 00:13:23.190
&gt;&gt; Kojo Nnamdi: What do you make
of the shift and the perception

00:13:23.190 --> 00:13:27.450
of graphic novels that the
"March" trilogy has been a part

00:13:27.450 --> 00:13:29.410
of and maybe a leader in?

00:13:29.410 --> 00:13:32.780
&gt;&gt; Andrew Aydin: I think we broke
the publishing system a little bit,

00:13:32.780 --> 00:13:37.190
and I think in a sense "March" is
putting it back together stronger

00:13:37.190 --> 00:13:39.050
than it was before.

00:13:39.050 --> 00:13:46.360
I don't think we set
out to do that, per se.

00:13:46.360 --> 00:13:48.250
We set out to tell
John Lewis' story.

00:13:48.250 --> 00:13:51.250
We set out to tell it in a way
that would reach more people

00:13:51.250 --> 00:13:54.140
than had ever been
reached by this story.

00:13:54.140 --> 00:13:58.220
But the result is, is I
think comics are coming

00:13:58.220 --> 00:14:00.970
of age because of the Internet.

00:14:00.970 --> 00:14:04.190
Because like all you all,
you all are digital natives.

00:14:04.190 --> 00:14:06.450
You grew up on the Internet.

00:14:06.450 --> 00:14:08.580
You communicate through
memes, right?

00:14:08.580 --> 00:14:13.920
Like they don't admit it, but like
you have whole conversations with,

00:14:13.920 --> 00:14:18.490
you know, success kid,
and everything else.

00:14:19.520 --> 00:14:21.740
And so, yeah, yeah,
somebody's [inaudible] okay.

00:14:21.740 --> 00:14:27.210
And so for this generation,
comics is there natural language.

00:14:27.210 --> 00:14:28.590
It is graphic narrative.

00:14:28.590 --> 00:14:31.650
It is, it is sequential
story telling.

00:14:31.650 --> 00:14:34.820
It is just simply how this
generation speaks to each other.

00:14:34.820 --> 00:14:38.590 position:56%
And so it was only a matter of time,
I think what we're most fortunate

00:14:38.590 --> 00:14:42.050
about is that it was John Lewis'
story that broke down that barrier.

00:14:42.050 --> 00:14:45.380
It was a little bit ahead of its
time, and so it was right there

00:14:45.380 --> 00:14:49.020
when it needed to be there
as opposed to, you know,

00:14:49.020 --> 00:14:54.330
we could all be celebrating the, I
don't know, the great puppy wars,

00:14:54.330 --> 00:14:57.460
or something, you know, that really
wouldn't resonate with us the way

00:14:57.460 --> 00:14:59.600
that John Lewis' story
does and that needs

00:14:59.600 --> 00:15:02.590
to be immortalized the way
John Lewis' story does.

00:15:02.590 --> 00:15:05.310
And so I think it was a combination
of being just a little bit ahead

00:15:05.310 --> 00:15:10.000 position:56%
of our time and being at the right
place for this generation to be able

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:12.840
to embrace it because
it's their language.

00:15:12.840 --> 00:15:14.960
&gt;&gt; Kojo Nnamdi: Congressman Lewis,
did it take a lot of convincing

00:15:14.960 --> 00:15:17.760
to get you involved in
writing what [inaudible].

00:15:17.760 --> 00:15:20.510
&gt;&gt; Rep. John Lewis: Well, Andrew,
I think probably would say,

00:15:20.510 --> 00:15:23.420
well, it took a little time.

00:15:23.420 --> 00:15:26.300
But he didn't give up, you know.

00:15:26.300 --> 00:15:31.500
He just said, Congressman,
you should write a comic book.

00:15:31.500 --> 00:15:34.680
I said, oh, maybe.

00:15:34.680 --> 00:15:39.120
He came back again, and I don't
know how many times he came back.

00:15:39.120 --> 00:15:40.420
&gt;&gt; Andrew Aydin: Who's counting?

00:15:40.420 --> 00:15:41.990
&gt;&gt; Rep. John Lewis:
We didn't keep count.

00:15:41.990 --> 00:15:48.220
[laughter] And I said, I
finally said something like, yes,

00:15:48.220 --> 00:15:52.580
if you do it with me,
and the rest is history.

00:15:52.580 --> 00:15:54.390
&gt;&gt; Kojo Nnamdi: Indeed,
a remarkable history.

