00:41:03.370 --> 00:41:06.770
and I got to know these chickens.

00:41:06.770 --> 00:41:12.980
I told them to be quiet, not
to make noise, not to fight,

00:41:12.980 --> 00:41:14.890
for them to love each other.

00:41:14.890 --> 00:41:18.210
&gt;&gt; Kojo Nnamdi: Any other
hands raised with questions?

00:41:18.210 --> 00:41:20.510
Right down here.

00:41:20.510 --> 00:41:24.110
[ Background Noise ]

00:41:24.110 --> 00:41:29.000 position:56%
&gt;&gt; So, actually last year our school
went on a field trip to a bunch

00:41:29.000 --> 00:41:37.120
of junior, or rangers' memorials
all around, all around the south,

00:41:37.120 --> 00:41:41.610
and so one of the places that
we actually went to was Selma,

00:41:41.610 --> 00:41:46.060 position:56%
and we walked across the bridge that
you walked across on, across on,

00:41:46.060 --> 00:41:50.930
so could you tell us what
some of your experiences were

00:41:50.930 --> 00:41:53.380
when you crossed that bridge?

00:41:53.380 --> 00:41:57.670
&gt;&gt; Kojo Nnamdi: When
you crossed the bridge.

00:41:57.670 --> 00:42:00.820
&gt;&gt; Rep. John Lewis: Yeah, in Selma,
Alabama, like so many other parts

00:42:00.820 --> 00:42:07.700
of the south, people of color
could not register to vote

00:42:07.700 --> 00:42:12.520
because of the color of their skin.

00:42:12.520 --> 00:42:19.530 position:56%
There were African American lawyers,
doctors, teachers, housewives,

00:42:19.530 --> 00:42:25.510 position:56%
and farmers were told that they
could not read or write well enough.

00:42:25.510 --> 00:42:28.360 position:56%
Sometimes people were asked to
count the number of bubbles in a bar

00:42:28.360 --> 00:42:33.770
of soap, the number of
jelly beans in a jar.

00:42:33.770 --> 00:42:41.020
One day more than 300 public school
teachers left school, lined up,

00:42:41.020 --> 00:42:47.170
and went down to the court house
to receive a copy of the test.

00:42:47.170 --> 00:42:49.000
The stood in line.

00:42:49.000 --> 00:42:52.840
The registrar closed the office,

00:42:52.840 --> 00:42:57.830
and they were denied the
right to register to vote.

00:42:57.830 --> 00:43:01.520
And a few days later as you
saw maybe in the movie Selma,

00:43:01.520 --> 00:43:10.020
a group of people marched, it
was a protest, in the home town

00:43:10.020 --> 00:43:14.850
of Mrs. Martin Luther King,
Jr., Loretta Scott King,

00:43:14.850 --> 00:43:21.070 position:56%
and one protester was shot and later
died at the local hospital in Selma.

00:43:21.070 --> 00:43:23.990
Because of what happened to
him, we made a decision to march

00:43:23.990 --> 00:43:25.980
from Selma to Montgomery.

00:43:25.980 --> 00:43:32.780
Six hundred of us in twos, orderly,
peaceful, no one saying a word.

00:43:32.780 --> 00:43:38.260
The night before the march, the
local sheriff, he was a mean man,

00:43:38.260 --> 00:43:45.630
really just mean, who wore a button
on his left lapel that said never.

00:43:45.630 --> 00:43:49.290
He carried an electric cow prodder,
and he didn't use it on cows.

00:43:49.290 --> 00:43:50.590
He used it on people.

00:43:50.590 --> 00:43:53.110
He would push people.

00:43:53.110 --> 00:43:59.410
He would beat people for exercising
their constitutional right.

00:43:59.410 --> 00:44:04.670
So on that bridge that Sunday,
we got to the highest point

00:44:04.670 --> 00:44:08.180
on the Edmund Pettus bridge,
down below we saw a sea of blue,

00:44:08.180 --> 00:44:11.950
Alabama state troopers,
and we continued to walk.

00:44:11.950 --> 00:44:14.490
We came within hearing distance.

00:44:14.490 --> 00:44:17.470
A man spoke up and said
I'm Major John Cloud

00:44:17.470 --> 00:44:19.700
of the Alabama state troopers.

00:44:19.700 --> 00:44:21.170
This is an unlawful march.

00:44:21.170 --> 00:44:23.030
It will not be allowed to continue.

00:44:23.030 --> 00:44:25.490
I give you three minutes
to disperse and return

00:44:25.490 --> 00:44:28.770
to your homes or to your church.

00:44:28.770 --> 00:44:34.220
And a young man walking
beside me, one of the leaders

00:44:34.220 --> 00:44:38.940
from Dr. King's organization by the
name of Jose Williams, said, Major,

00:44:38.940 --> 00:44:40.620
give us a moment to kneel and pray.

00:44:40.620 --> 00:44:44.730
And the Major said,
troopers advance.

00:44:44.730 --> 00:44:47.320
I said Major, may I have a word?

00:44:47.320 --> 00:44:49.680
He said, there will be no word.

00:44:49.680 --> 00:44:55.910
They came, beating us with night
sticks, trampling with horses,

00:44:55.910 --> 00:44:58.010
releasing their tear gas.

00:44:58.010 --> 00:45:01.540
I was hit in the head by a state
trooper with a night stick.

00:45:01.540 --> 00:45:03.010
My legs went from under me.

00:45:03.010 --> 00:45:04.310
I thought I saw death.

00:45:04.310 --> 00:45:06.410
I thought I was going
to die on that bridge.

00:45:06.410 --> 00:45:09.510
I thought it was the
last nonviolent protest.

00:45:09.510 --> 00:45:13.910
And all these many years later,
I don't recall how I made it back

00:45:13.910 --> 00:45:18.840
across that bridge to the little
church that we had left from,

00:45:18.840 --> 00:45:22.980
but I remember being in the
church and someone asked me

00:45:22.980 --> 00:45:25.220
to say something, and I
stood up and said something

00:45:25.220 --> 00:45:29.230
like I don't understand it how
President Johnson can send troops

00:45:29.230 --> 00:45:34.670 position:56%
to Vietnam but cannot send troops
to Selma, Alabama, to protect people

00:45:34.670 --> 00:45:37.250 position:56%
who only desire to register to vote.

00:45:37.250 --> 00:45:44.770
The next thing I knew, with 16
other people, we was transferred

00:45:44.770 --> 00:45:49.520
to a little hospital where a
group of nuns took care of us.

00:45:49.520 --> 00:45:54.630
And last, just before the
election, late last October,

00:45:54.630 --> 00:46:01.080
I went to Rochester, New York, to
campaign for one of my colleagues

00:46:01.080 --> 00:46:05.040
in New York, they took me
to the mother house there,

00:46:05.040 --> 00:46:12.660
some of the nuns are retired, and
I saw this stained-glass window

00:46:12.660 --> 00:46:16.820
that had been in this hospital,
it's now in Rochester, New York,

00:46:16.820 --> 00:46:20.920
and some of the nuns that
took care me, they was there.

00:46:20.920 --> 00:46:27.130 position:56%
They remembered me, and they started
saying John, John, good to see you.

00:46:27.130 --> 00:46:32.590
And we all cried together.

00:46:32.590 --> 00:46:35.670
&gt;&gt; Kojo Nnamdi: Andrew Aydin, one
of the things that struck me most

00:46:35.670 --> 00:46:38.340
in reading this trilogy
was how John Lewis

00:46:38.340 --> 00:46:44.920
and the other protesters trained
themselves to respond nonviolently

00:46:44.920 --> 00:46:48.130
to the most violent
attacks by both civilians

00:46:48.130 --> 00:46:50.780
and law enforcement officers.

00:46:50.780 --> 00:46:53.280
You are even younger than I am.

00:46:53.280 --> 00:46:55.980
How did that strike you?

00:46:55.980 --> 00:47:00.580
&gt;&gt; Andrew Aydin: It felt like the
most important factor we could

00:47:00.580 --> 00:47:01.880
possibly convey.

00:47:01.880 --> 00:47:05.650 position:56%
I think many of us understand the
broad strokes of civil disobedience.

00:47:05.650 --> 00:47:09.810
Maybe we have read Thoreau or
Emerson or something like that,

00:47:09.810 --> 00:47:13.250
but really understanding the
nitty gritty, the details,

00:47:13.250 --> 00:47:16.640
the perseverance, and
the self-control it takes

00:47:16.640 --> 00:47:21.240
to be a successful protestor

00:47:21.240 --> 00:47:25.750
or a successful activist
using civil disobedience.

00:47:25.750 --> 00:47:28.190
And over and over and over
again as you read these texts,

00:47:28.190 --> 00:47:31.870
as you read the accounts,
the defining characteristic

00:47:31.870 --> 00:47:34.700
of the most successful
protest is how orderly

00:47:34.700 --> 00:47:36.920
and how disciplined they were.

00:47:36.920 --> 00:47:41.130
And so for us, showing
that discipline is part

00:47:41.130 --> 00:47:45.040
of the visual narrative of what
allows it to be more successful

00:47:45.040 --> 00:47:50.450
in the visual medium is showing
that discipline, not just telling,

00:47:50.450 --> 00:47:52.820 position:56%
showing how much they had to endure,

00:47:52.820 --> 00:47:54.860
whether it's the cigarettes
being put out in your hair,

00:47:54.860 --> 00:47:58.020
the hot coffee being
poured down your back,

00:47:58.020 --> 00:48:01.490
having you friends call you names.

00:48:01.490 --> 00:48:06.710
It was the most important
thing we could convey.

00:48:06.710 --> 00:48:09.300
&gt;&gt; Kojo Nnamdi: Any other
questions from students here?

00:48:09.300 --> 00:48:12.310
Right here.

00:48:12.310 --> 00:48:13.980
Ma'am?

00:48:13.980 --> 00:48:17.290
&gt;&gt; This question is for both
of you all, you all say a lot

00:48:17.290 --> 00:48:22.290
about positivity, so do you guys
see similarities in today's actions

00:48:22.290 --> 00:48:27.240
as far as protesting
you did in your day?

00:48:27.240 --> 00:48:30.850
&gt;&gt; Rep. John Lewis: Well,
today, I see similarities.

00:48:30.850 --> 00:48:40.260 position:56%
The women marched just a few days, a
few weeks ago, whether in Washington

00:48:40.260 --> 00:48:45.170
or in Atlanta, around the
nation, around the world,

00:48:45.170 --> 00:48:51.340
people use the same
techniques and tactics.

00:48:51.340 --> 00:48:56.940
Some of the music was a
little more upbeat, and music,

00:48:56.940 --> 00:49:03.810
Andrew would tell you, research,
music is very, very powerful.

00:49:03.810 --> 00:49:07.270
I said on occasion, if
it hadn't been for music,

00:49:07.270 --> 00:49:11.820 position:56%
the civil rights movement would
have been like a bird without wings.

00:49:11.820 --> 00:49:13.120
It brought us together.

00:49:13.120 --> 00:49:17.030
It created a sense of
family, a sense of solidarity

00:49:17.030 --> 00:49:21.710
that we we're all in this thing
together, and sometimes when,

00:49:21.710 --> 00:49:27.190 position:56%
so during the freedom rides in 1961,
when we were arrested in Jackson,

00:49:27.190 --> 00:49:31.420
Mississippi, we filled the city
jail, and later people kept coming.

00:49:31.420 --> 00:49:33.220
We filled the county jail.

00:49:33.220 --> 00:49:35.230
Then they took us to the heart

00:49:35.230 --> 00:49:38.700
of the delta [inaudible]
state penitentiary,

00:49:38.700 --> 00:49:42.610
and the people would say, the
guards, the jailers would say,

00:49:42.610 --> 00:49:45.200
if you don't stop singing
those songs,

00:49:45.200 --> 00:49:47.380
we're going to take your mattress.

00:49:47.380 --> 00:49:48.730
And people would make up songs.

00:49:48.730 --> 00:49:53.290
Andrew probably, and maybe
would sing one of them.

00:49:53.290 --> 00:49:56.190
&gt;&gt; Andrew Aydin: So
low you can't hear me.

00:49:56.190 --> 00:50:00.490
&gt;&gt; Rep. John Lewis: But today
you see people coming together

00:50:00.490 --> 00:50:05.700
in an orderly, peaceful,
nonviolent fashion.

00:50:05.700 --> 00:50:07.050
I was so proud.

00:50:07.050 --> 00:50:09.430
I marched with the
people in Atlanta.

00:50:09.430 --> 00:50:12.530
More than 63,000 people showed up.

00:50:12.530 --> 00:50:16.510
And hundreds and thousands from
Atlanta came to Washington.

00:50:16.510 --> 00:50:20.550
And people showed up at
the airport in an orderly,

00:50:20.550 --> 00:50:23.710
peaceful, nonviolent fashion.

00:50:23.710 --> 00:50:26.410
They learned they're
starting the movement.

00:50:26.410 --> 00:50:28.630
It was very similar.

00:50:28.630 --> 00:50:30.510
Andrew, I know you
have something to add.

00:50:30.510 --> 00:50:35.040
[ Background Noise ]

00:50:35.040 --> 00:50:39.710 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Andrew Aydin: Well, I'm not going
to sing, but I think when you talk

00:50:39.710 --> 00:50:46.010
about creating the climate,
creating the environment for change

00:50:46.010 --> 00:50:55.170
to happen, music, pop culture, I
think in this day and age we have

00:50:55.170 --> 00:50:56.470
to look beyond [inaudible].

00:50:56.470 --> 00:50:58.090
They play a role.

00:50:58.090 --> 00:51:04.390
But at the end of the day people

00:51:04.390 --> 00:51:08.420
with conscience coming
together for a purpose.

00:51:08.420 --> 00:51:13.870
I marched-- I'm going to blow out
you all speakers at this rate.

00:51:13.870 --> 00:51:21.930
I marched here in DC, and I've
never seen anything quite like it.

00:51:21.930 --> 00:51:27.830
I was at Barack Obama's
inauguration in 2009.

00:51:27.830 --> 00:51:29.750
I staffed the Congressman that day.

00:51:29.750 --> 00:51:32.370
I walked through the crowds.

00:51:32.370 --> 00:51:35.440
It was peaceful, and
it was optimistic,

00:51:35.440 --> 00:51:39.720 position:56%
but the sense of revolution wasn't--

00:51:39.720 --> 00:51:45.830
in 2009, we thought
we were finished.

00:51:45.830 --> 00:51:48.150 position:56%
Right. And that's why 2010 happened.

00:51:48.150 --> 00:51:52.210 position:56%
And that's what started this tumble,
but what happened at the march,

00:51:52.210 --> 00:51:57.080
the women's march, what's happened
in the days and weeks since then,

00:51:57.080 --> 00:52:03.230
it's not just about optimism,
it's about a sense of duty,

00:52:03.230 --> 00:52:07.690
that we all recognize
maybe we didn't do as much

00:52:07.690 --> 00:52:11.460
as we should have beforehand,
but we all say

00:52:11.460 --> 00:52:14.760
with a collective voice,
it stops now.

00:52:14.760 --> 00:52:17.810 position:56%
We all have something to contribute,
and we all will contribute.

00:52:17.810 --> 00:52:24.390
I think that very much
permeated that same feeling.

00:52:24.390 --> 00:52:27.590
Maybe in the latter days,
from what I understand,

00:52:27.590 --> 00:52:32.630 position:56%
it got lost in the freedom highs
and things like that, but that sense

00:52:32.630 --> 00:52:39.030
that we all have something to
contribute, and that we will rage

00:52:39.030 --> 00:52:47.130
against injustice, together, is
the most powerful development

00:52:47.130 --> 00:52:51.130
in my own life that I've ever
witnessed of our society.

00:52:53.770 --> 00:52:59.530
And I hope you're prepared
because we need you next.

00:52:59.530 --> 00:53:03.820
And it's not going to be easy.

00:53:03.820 --> 00:53:10.010
I spent most of the time
making "March" being afraid,

00:53:10.010 --> 00:53:16.030
and the Congressman telling me,
no, no, the best is yet to come.

00:53:16.030 --> 00:53:17.700 position:56%
I didn't know if we would finish it.

00:53:17.700 --> 00:53:19.300
I didn't know if it
would be any good.

00:53:19.300 --> 00:53:22.310
I didn't know if I would do a
good enough job honoring the

00:53:22.310 --> 00:53:24.480
Congressman's story.

00:53:24.480 --> 00:53:26.320
We're telling the story of all
the people whose stories needed

00:53:26.320 --> 00:53:27.620
to be told.

00:53:27.620 --> 00:53:33.590
And that was just one small piece,
so it's okay for you to be afraid,

00:53:33.590 --> 00:53:39.460
but you got to be hopeful, and you
got to understand that the progress

00:53:39.460 --> 00:53:41.560
of this country is on
your shoulders next.

00:53:41.560 --> 00:53:43.620
And my generation,
Kojo's generation,

00:53:43.620 --> 00:53:46.250
and the Congressman's generation,

00:53:46.250 --> 00:53:50.510
we're doing everything we can
right now, but we need you.

00:53:50.510 --> 00:53:56.040
[ Background Noise ]

00:53:56.040 --> 00:53:57.340
&gt;&gt; Kojo Nnamdi: Anyone else?

00:53:57.340 --> 00:53:58.640
We have time for one more question,

00:53:58.640 --> 00:54:02.060
and needless to say there
are four hands raised.

00:54:02.060 --> 00:54:04.200
Young man?

00:54:04.200 --> 00:54:05.540
&gt;&gt; Hi. This is just for Mr. Lewis,

00:54:05.540 --> 00:54:07.790
but what do you think was
the most important thing

00:54:07.790 --> 00:54:10.060
that came out of the march?

00:54:10.060 --> 00:54:11.360
&gt;&gt; Rep. John Lewis:
Out of the march?

00:54:11.360 --> 00:54:12.660
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:54:12.660 --> 00:54:14.960
&gt;&gt; Rep. John Lewis: Well, because
of the march, because of the march,

00:54:14.960 --> 00:54:18.210
excuse me, because of the march,

00:54:18.210 --> 00:54:20.850
I've been talking too
much, I'm losing my voice.

00:54:20.850 --> 00:54:22.150
&gt;&gt; Andrew Aydin: Drink some water.

00:54:22.150 --> 00:54:23.450
&gt;&gt; Rep. John Lewis: Thank you.

00:54:23.450 --> 00:54:25.180
I was in a committee meeting today.

00:54:25.180 --> 00:54:26.480
I had holler a little bit.

00:54:26.480 --> 00:54:27.780
&gt;&gt; Andrew Aydin: Good trouble.

00:54:27.780 --> 00:54:29.180
&gt;&gt; Rep. John Lewis: I
had to preach a little.

00:54:29.180 --> 00:54:30.480
[laughter]

00:54:30.480 --> 00:54:33.210
&gt;&gt; Andrew Aydin: I got it.

00:54:33.210 --> 00:54:35.010
&gt;&gt; Rep. John Lewis: Thank you.

00:54:35.010 --> 00:54:44.070
[ Background Noise ]

00:54:44.070 --> 00:54:49.910
The march from Selma to Montgomery
gave us the Voting Rights Act

00:54:49.910 --> 00:54:53.530
of 1965.

00:54:53.530 --> 00:54:59.370
It educated, it inspired so
many people to stand out,

00:54:59.370 --> 00:55:03.530
to say to Congress, say to the
President of the United States,

00:55:03.530 --> 00:55:07.310 position:56%
we need to pass a Voting Rights Act.

00:55:07.310 --> 00:55:13.790
Because of what happened on
Bloody Sunday, March 7th,

00:55:13.790 --> 00:55:20.930
the President of the United States,
Lyndon Johnson, President Johnson,

00:55:20.930 --> 00:55:22.810
came and spoke to [inaudible]
session

00:55:22.810 --> 00:55:27.870
of the Congress and
introduced a bill.

00:55:27.870 --> 00:55:32.890
We completed the march,
and on August 6, 1965,

00:55:32.890 --> 00:55:36.230
the Voting Rights Act
was signed into law.

00:55:36.230 --> 00:55:40.480
Hundreds and thousands and
millions of people were registered

00:55:40.480 --> 00:55:43.550
to vote for the first time.

00:55:43.550 --> 00:55:45.840
If it hadn't been for
the Voting Rights Act,

00:55:45.840 --> 00:55:53.600
I'm not so sure President
Carter and President Clinton

00:55:53.600 --> 00:55:59.100
and President Obama would
have been elected President.

00:55:59.100 --> 00:56:03.110
And I probably wouldn't
be in Congress,

00:56:03.110 --> 00:56:09.660
and many other local elected
officials, black, white, Latinos,

00:56:09.660 --> 00:56:14.770
Asian American, wouldn't
be in the Congress,

00:56:14.770 --> 00:56:17.180
but we still have a distance to go

00:56:17.180 --> 00:56:25.340
because the Supreme Court almost
destroyed the Voting Rights Act two

00:56:25.340 --> 00:56:27.210
years ago.

00:56:27.210 --> 00:56:30.960
So we still have work to do.

00:56:30.960 --> 00:56:33.620
&gt;&gt; Kojo Nnamdi: And it
rests on the shoulders

00:56:33.620 --> 00:56:36.910
of your generation to some extent.

00:56:36.910 --> 00:56:39.440
I'm afraid that's all
the time we have.

00:56:39.440 --> 00:56:43.290
But thank you to Karen Jaffe
[phonetic] and the entire team here

00:56:43.290 --> 00:56:45.510
at the Library of Congress'
Young Readers [inaudible].

00:56:45.510 --> 00:56:54.090
[ Applause ]

00:56:54.090 --> 00:56:55.390
Thank you to librarian of Congress,

00:56:55.390 --> 00:56:57.510
Carla Hayden [phonetic],
get well soon.

00:56:57.510 --> 00:57:02.060
[ Applause ]

00:57:02.060 --> 00:57:05.490
Thank you to everybody in DC for
bringing in this wonderful audience

00:57:05.490 --> 00:57:09.510
and for sending them home
with copies of the book.

00:57:09.510 --> 00:57:14.600
[ Applause ]

00:57:14.600 --> 00:57:19.370
And last but obviously not
least, thanks to Andrew Aydin

00:57:19.370 --> 00:57:23.510
and Congressman John Lewis
for sharing their story.

00:57:23.510 --> 00:57:34.040
[ Applause ]

00:57:34.040 --> 00:57:37.200
I'll close with the words of
the later writer Frantz Fanon,

00:57:37.200 --> 00:57:42.790 position:56%
who wrote, "It is the role of each
generation out of relative obscurity

00:57:42.790 --> 00:57:48.630
to discover its missions and
either fulfill it or betray it."

00:57:48.630 --> 00:57:50.960
Go forth and fulfill your mission.

00:57:50.960 --> 00:57:52.760
Thank you very much for being here.

00:57:52.760 --> 00:58:01.050
[ Applause ]

00:58:01.050 --> 00:58:03.850
